<p>So, normally I do like this:</p>  <pre><code>var duplicate = this.model.collection.some(function(model){    return (model.get('hook') == h); }); </code></pre>  <p>Fine. But in backbone docs, under collection's underscore methods, I find this:</p>  <p><em>'Most methods can take an object or string to support model-attribute-style predicates'</em></p>  <p>So I imagined I could refactor the above like this:</p>  <pre><code>var duplicate = this.model.collection.some({'hook':h}); </code></pre>  <p>But it doesn't work. So what does exactly mean that doc's statement?</p>